 revisit canonical works – by Claudia Andujar and George Love, Mohamed Bourouissa, Walker Evans, Susan Meiselas and Roland Penrose – while also delving into institutional, digital and unrealised projects, illegal practices, DIY communities and the poetic impulse. They throw new light on the way that gendered, racial or colonial assumptions are resisted. Taken as a whole, the volume provides a better understanding of how the meaning of a photobook is collectively produced both inside and outside the art market.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPhotobooksxHistory. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh  aClaudia Andujar.  aMartin Parr.  aMohamed Bourouissa.  aRoland Penrose.  aSusan Meiselas.  aVisual Studies Workshop.  aWalker Evans.  aart world.  aobject biography.  aphotobook market.  aphotobook.1 aBaudouin, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlinder, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, Jessie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlin, Briony Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahmani, Taous R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Paul Ernest Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEdwards, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards-Grossi, Élodie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcelino, Vitor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, Jessica S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeumüller, Moritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanzer, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc